Here is an implementation of a queue using two stacks in Python:

```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.instack = []
        self.outstack = []

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.instack.append(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if not self.outstack:
            while self.instack:
                self.outstack.append(self.instack.pop())
        return self.outstack.pop()
```

The key idea is to use one stack (instack) to enqueue new items by simply appending to it. To dequeue an item, we first check if the outstack is empty. If so, we pop all elements from the instack and push them onto the outstack. This reverses the order of the elements, turning the LIFO instack into a FIFO outstack. Finally we pop and return the top element of the outstack as the dequeued item.

This allows enqueue and dequeue operations in amortized O(1) time complexity while using O(n) extra space for the stacks.

